<TEXT>
cuban angolan and south african 
delegates discussing the timetable for independence for namibia 
adjourned their talks early tuesday but will meet again a south 
african general told reporters 
gen jannie geldenhuys gave no details but said we have not 
terminated our discussions and the delegates would consult their 
governments before meeting again 
then he said the talks would resume friday at a location in 
angola to be announced 
geldenhuys was asked about reports that south africa wanted to 
know if the delegations could be certain that all guerrillas 
fighting south african administration of the territory have 
withdrawn 
that is still under discussion and will be pursued friday 
he said 
south africa has said the independence process could be 
endangered if significant numbers of guerrillas of the southwest 
africal peoples organization remain in namibia and do not return 
to their bases in angola 
namibia also known as southwest africa has been administered 
by south africa since world war i 
south africa agreed in december to end its control of the 
territory under a regional peace plan that also requires cuba to 
withdraw its estimated 50000 soldiers from angola the cubans have 
helped angolas marxist government fight the ussupported rebels 
representatives of the three nations along with us and soviet 
observers met monday and early tuesday at a site about 600 yards 
north of the namibian border and near the angolan town of ruacana 
the talks are seen as crucial to the unsponsored plan to make 
namibia independent next year 
the yearlong transition was derailed april 1 the day it began 
when an estimated 1600 swapo guerrillas entered namibia despite an 
agreement that they remain at their bases in angola at least until 
midmay 
south african officials said 316 guerrillas and 27 members of 
the namibian security forces were killed in fighting before swapo 
ordered its men to return to angola 
the joint commission is also expected to discuss a new date for 
swapo rebels to be allowed to enter namibia peacefully some 
officials have said the return originally set for may 15 could 
start may 22 
namibian elections are scheduled to be held in november before 
the annual rainy season that disrupts travel some observers say 
that a significant postponement of the timetable could prevent 
elections before next february after the rains have stopped 
</TEXT>
