<TEXT>
the first us military dependents and 
personnel evacuated from panama arrived tuesday night aboard a 
chartered commercial jet and one said the situation there was 
bad and getting worse 
the blueandwhite l1011 with 276 defense department personnel 
and family members landed at charleston international airport 
around 1045 pm 
the first group of tiredlooking passengers several carrying 
infants and small children entered the terminal about 10 minutes 
later to begin clearance through customs 
the situation in panama is bad and getting worse said army 
sgt raymond johnson of el paso texas johnson was bringing by his 
wife daughter and son back to stay with his family in el paso 
being a family man i felt it would be safer to have my family 
here he said johnson said members of the panamanian defense 
force often harass american personnel stopping them on the streets 
and sometimes asking for money 
i just decided to go home and get out and let it settle 
down said debbie strong of washington state who was carrying an 
infant she said her husband is in the army and she works on a base 
in panama 
a second flight is scheduled to arrive late wednesday said air 
force lt lester t carroll jr a spokesman for the 437th military 
airlift wing 
were calling this a hastened withdrawal said army lt col 
bob skinner a defense department spokesman from fort mcpherson 
ga who was at the airport 
an evacuation is mandatory skinner said this is not an 
emergency it is voluntary carroll called the move 
precautionary 
the defense department earlier tuesday offered immediate 
evacuations to any of the 14000 military dependents in panama 
carroll said he did not know how much notice the military 
dependents were given before leaving panama 
he said some passed through charleston on monday on a regularly 
scheduled military charter 
the flights to charleston are regularly scheduled military 
charter flights skinner said 
he said he did not know of any additional flights beyond the one 
scheduled for wednesday night 
however military sources who asked not to be identified said 
they expected at least one and possibly two flights would be staged 
each day for military families wishing to leave panama 
those who arrived tuesday were to spend the night at charleston 
air force base hotels or friends in the area skinner said 
some were expected to take connecting flights out of charleston 
as early as 6 am wednesday 
