<TEXT>
rain like wealth is plentiful is some areas 
while other parts of the united states are living handtomouth so 
to speak 
in ohio part of the eastern corn belt that has been drenched 
lately farmers had planted only 13 percent of their corn acreage 
by may 14 compared with 87 percent a year ago and the normal 
midmay progress of 72 percent 
a report by the agriculture department on tuesday following a 
meeting of the departments 1989 drought task force said rain 
continues to delay spring planting in some areas while others 
notably the central and southern great plains still need moisture 
planting is delayed by wet cool weather in eastern corn belt 
delta and east coast areas but is progressing rapidly in western 
great lakes western corn belt and spring wheat areas the report 
said 
iowa minnesota south dakota wisconsin and michigan have 
planted 30 percent to 43 percent of their corn crop north dakota 
montana and minnesota have planted about onethird of their spring 
wheat it added 
the report was issued following a meeting of the departments 
1989 drought task force which is headed by undersecretary richard 
crowder 
winter wheat conditions improved in the pacific northwest and 
northern great plains but deteriorated in the central and southern 
great plains the report said the crop moisture index 
indicates excellent moisture for germination of recently planted 
crops in the great plains great lakes and central corn belt 
the task force noted that the national weather service calls for 
beneficial rains in the great plains and central corn belt in the 
next five to 10 days with favorably drier weather in the eastern 
corn belt 
the outlook through midjune calls for cool wet weather in 
the south and east and warm dry weather from the eastern dakotas 
into the central corn belt the report said 
looking at the livestock situation the report said pasture 
conditions nationally are rated poor to fair but that the 
situation in much of the northern plains is very poor to severe 
cattle slaughter is down 4 percent from a year ago but last 
weeks slaughter figures were the same as at this time last year 
the report said beef cow slaughter was up arouind 60 percent 
in both the central and northern plains however cow prices in 
recent weeks have returned to 1987 levels reflecting the effects 
of increased slaughter 
the task force said that as of may 15 haying and grazing of 
land normally idled during the growing season under acreage 
conservation provisions were open for haying and grazing in 323 
counties of eight states california iowa kansas missouri 
nebraska new mexico north dakota and texas 
emergency feed assistance along with haying and grazing of 
other designated conservation land also has been made available in 
designated counties of the drought areas in all some form of 
special drought aid is available in hundreds of counties in more 
than two dozen states 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the agriculture department says a virus called 
abby shows promise of being an effective killer of foliageeating 
gypsy moths 
entomologist martin shapiro of the departments agricultural 
research service said tuesday that once the virus is applied it is 
transmitted to each new generation of moths 
the agency and the forest service plan to field test the abby 
virus this summer in western maryland scientists will count the 
number of dead moth larvae and measure the amount of foliage that 
was protected 
shapiro said that if abby passes the tests the virus could 
become an alternative to either bacillus thuringiensis bacteria or 
diflubenzuron a chemical presently used against the moths by 
keeping them from reaching adulthood 
shapiro who has worked on the virus strain for about seven 
years at the agencys insect pathology laboratory in beltsville 
md named the new virus abby after the town where it was found 
abington mass 
the abby virus showed up early in the studies as one of the most 
effective of 19 different strains of nuclear polyhdrosis virus or 
npv around the world the npv strains infect gypsy caterpillars 
but may not always prevent them from defoliating trees 
but shapiro said the abby virus showed in laboratory tests that 
it can kill more caterpillars 10 times faster than the standard 
npv which has been used for two years by the national park service 
in selected areas of rock creek park in washington dc 
park officials said that wherever npv was sprayed there was 
little or no defoliation to the trees shapiro said and that 
was the natural strain not abby 
gypsy moths in the caterpillar or larvae stage are voracious 
eaters of foliage and have gradually spread from massachusetts 
where they were imported in 1969 by a french biologist to breed 
with native american silkworms 
but the moths escaped from the laboratory and started eating 
foliage the scientist louis trouvellot returned to france and 
pursued a career in astronomy 
</TEXT>
