<DOCNO> AP890517-0030 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
stringent recordkeeping requirements in a 
child antipornography statute are unconstitutional according to a 
federal judge who said the restrictions infringe on first amendment 
rights 
us district judge george revercomb on tuesday handed down the 
decision on the 1988 child protection and obscenity enforcement 
act which requires publishers and distributors to document the 
ages of nude models in photographs 
under the law models and performers must be contacted to 
determine if they were at least 18 years old at the time the 
photograph or film was made the requirements cover the reissue of 
images first made after feb 6 1978 the date of the chief federal 
law criminalizing child pornography said the judge 
the requirements have not been narrowly tailored to fit the 
legitimate governmental interest of stopping child pornography 
revercomb said in a 43page decision they burden too heavily and 
infringe too deeply on the right to produce material protected by 
the first amendment he wrote 
the result of the requirement will undoubtedly be the 
effective prohibition of the distribution of much first amendment 
protected material the opinion said 
the ruling came in a lawsuit filed by the american library 
association 
revercomb also found unconstitutional companion requirements 
providing for a presumption of criminality by those who fail to 
abide by recordkeeping requirements 
proof that a person being prosecuted for a child porn offense 
failed to keep the proper records shall raise a rebuttable 
presumption that such performer was a minor according to the law 
revercomb said the criminal presumptions raise the serious 
potential for convicting people who have not engaged in child 
pornography 
the judge also found unconstitutional parts of a civil provision 
in the child pornography law and portions of a criminal forfeiture 
provision allowing seizure of materials before conviction 
the provisions allow forfeiture of property used to promote the 
commission of an offense revercomb blocked the government from 
enforcing the provisions unless there has been a prior adversarial 
proceeding 
the court also enjoined the government from enforcing the 
postconviction forfeiture provisions of the law unless there has 
been a pattern of activity 
the laws at issue here appear to authorize forfeiture of vast 
amounts of assets everything from first amendment protected 
material to bank accounts for a single violation said the 
judge 
justice department spokeswoman amy brown said the department was 
still reviewing the opinion and studying its impact and had no 
further immediate comment 
bruce ennis an attorney representing the american library 
association said last month the law puts nearimpossible 
recordkeeping burdens on legitimate businesses it would impose a 
corporate death penalty on distributors because all assets 
could be seized if they violate the law with even one publication 
ennis said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

