<DOCNO> AP890517-0031 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
rep john bryant is seeking to severely 
restrict the practice of clearcutting in national forests calling 
the timber harvesting method irresponsible and wasteful 
but the us forest service and industry representatives say 
clearcutting timber is a valuable forest management tool and is 
vital to maintaining habitat for certain species of wildlife 
clearcutting ignores the need for natural species diversity 
as a requirement for a healthy forest environment bryant 
dtexas said tuesday 
he was referring to the practice of cutting down all the trees 
in an area rather than selectively picking trees to fell 
a live healthy forest is replaced after a clearcut with a 
single species of tree plantation which forest experts believe 
loses its immunity to natural infestations of treekilling pests 
such as the southern pine beetle bryant said 
bryant introduced legislation to prohibit clearcutting in any 
national forest in which onetenth of the acreage of available 
commercial timberland has already been harvested by clearcutting 
many national forests would be affected he said 
the forest service would be required to replace clearcutting 
with selectionmanagement harvesting techniques in which only 
certain trees are removed from a stand and a diversity of plants 
remain 
although backed by some environmentalists bryant acknowledged a 
tough fight ahead and intense pressure from timber industry 
lobbyists to prevent a serious hearing on the bill 
last year 283061 acres of national forest were clearcut 
bryant said national forests cover 191 million acres of which 61 
million are classified as suitable for timber production 
dave hessel director of timber management at the forest 
service said clearcutting is valuable in maintaining not only 
species diversity but also in its relationship to maintaining 
wildlife habitat needs 
hessel said clearcutting is needed for stands of trees that 
require sunlight to develop like the lodgepole pine lodgepole 
pine forests provide the habitat for big game species like elk in 
the rocky mountains 
the roughly 300000 acres that are clearcut represent about half 
the acreage harvested in national forests but produce 75 percent 
of the volume hessel said 
mark rey vice president for public forestry at national forest 
products association said clearcutting is not inconsistent with 
high wildlife values species diversity and multiple uses for 
forests 
rey also contends the bill would indisputably reduce the 
amount of timber production potential the lands can have because 
some species must have sunlight to regenerate 
</TEXT>
