<TEXT>
parliament approved laws today that 
guarantee freedom of worship and give legal status to the roman 
catholic church formally ending the communist states fourdecade 
struggle with the church 
passage of the three bills is expected to clear the way to 
formal diplomatic ties with the vatican which for years has 
refused to grant relations until the polish churchs legal status 
was resolved 
if ties are normalized it would make poland the first east bloc 
country to have such relations with the holy see 
the bills were introduced last month by prime minister 
mieczyslaw f rakowski and they passed without serious opposition 
in the sejm or parliament 
one bill defines the states attitude toward the church as a 
sovereign organization operating within the constitution but free 
to manage its internal affairs it passed the 460member sejm with 
two votes against and 12 absentions 
a second bill grants equal rights to all denominations bars 
discrimination based on religion and guarantees freedom of worship 
three lawmakers voted against it and three abstained 
the third bill entitles clergy to state oldage pensions it 
passed with seven votes against and 10 abstentions 
the legislation was drafted as a result of protracted 
negotiations between the roman catholic church and the government 
more than 90 percent of poles consider themselves catholic and 
in recent years the state had abandoned atheistic propaganda and 
sought to portray itself as tolerant of religious faith 
the laws passed today in effect replace an agreement between 
church and state that existed before world war ii but was abrogated 
when communists took power after the war 
we have been waiting for this law for 37 years said marek 
pernal a spokesman in the episcopate press office in warsaw 
in the 1940s and 1950s church property was seized and clergy 
were arrestd the roman catholic primate at the time cardinal 
stefan wyszynski was held prisoner for three years from 1953 to 
1956 
since former krakow archbishop karol wojtyla became pope john 
paul ii in 1978 the state has moved to patch up relations with the 
church seeing it as a stabilizing factor in the countrys often 
volatile politics 
church officials were instrumental in helping to set up the 
talks that led to the accord that legalized the solidarity trade 
union and allowed opposition participation in elections 
some poles recently have expressed concern about the degree of 
church influence in public life the church supports a bill before 
the sejm that would make abortion a crime punishable by three years 
in prison abortion has been legal in poland since 1956 
</TEXT>
