<TEXT>
the american campaign academy which was 
created to train political professionals does not qualify for a 
federal tax exemption because its work benefits republican 
candidates almost exclusively the us tax court ruled wednesday 
no graduate is known to have affiliated with any domestic 
political party other than the republican party chief judge 
arthur l nims iii wrote for the court 
we find that petitioner the academy operated to advance 
republican interests we also find that the placement of 85 of 
petitioners graduates in the campaigns of 98 republican senatorial 
and congressional candidates in 1986 conferred a benefit on those 
candidates the court concluded 
the academy located in arlington va had applied to the 
internal revenue service for a tax exemption as a charitable 
educational organization the irs rejected the application on 
grounds the academy failed to established that it was operated 
exclusively for taxexempt purposes 
you are operated for a substantial nonexempt private 
purpose the irs had ruled you benefit republican party 
entities and candidates more than incidentally also your 
activities serve the private interests of republican party entities 
rather than public interests exclusively 
the academy appealed that decision to the tax court and lost 
the academy was incorporated in january 1986 as an outgrowth of 
the national republican congressional committee which is composed 
of gop members of the house of representatives funding for the 
academy is provided exclusively by the national republican 
congressional trust 
two of the academys initial directors were joseph gaylord 
executive director of the committee and john c mcdonald a member 
of the republican national committee 
according to court records the academy limits enrollment to 
those aspiring to become campaign managers fundraisers or 
communications specialists although the academy keeps no records 
of political affiliations it acknowledged that a substantial 
number of its students as well as members of its admissions panel 
are affiliated with the gop 
the academy contended that whatever private benefit went to the 
gop was incidental to a broader interest of educating the public 
the court held that the academy was created primarily to further 
gop interests 
had the record established that the academys activities were 
nonpartisan in nature and that its graduates were not intended to 
primarily benefit republicans we would have a different case 
nims wrote we are not however deciding such a case 
</TEXT>
