least avoided legislative gridlock said house minority leader 
robert michel rill 
but progress is expected to be slower on a multibilliondollar 
spending bill for this year which has been mired because of 
disputes over money it contains for antidrug initiatives 
were going to get it up as soon as we can house 
appropriations committee chairman jamie whitten dmiss said 
tuesday after a day of closeddoor talks about the measure 
if congress kept to its schedule on the much less controversial 
1990 budget no serious opposition was expected it would be the 
earliest lawmakers have disposed of the spending plan since 1978 
the legislators speed is attributable to two factors 
one is that overall totals for defense and domestic spending 
and other tough decisions such as the 997 billion deficit it 
contains were decided last month by bush administration officials 
and congressional leaders of both parties 
the other is that the spending plan contains little real pain 
despite its effort to lop 28 billion off the federal deficit many 
lawmakers and other critics have said this is accomplished with 
optimistic economic projections that make the shortfall seem 
smaller and onetime gimmicks such as claiming 18 billion in 
savings by moving the postal service off budget 
science education health housing and law enforcement spending 
would receive healthy increases 
defense spending would rise to 2992 billion 42 billion 
short of the amount needed to keep up with inflation agriculture 
and transportation programs would also be pinched the measure 
calls for 53 billion in new tax receipts but the decision on 
where it would come from will be made later 
on tuesday the bush administration tried to coax congressional 
democrats to finally pass a 1989 spending bill that includes 340 
million for veterans health programs 
veterans affairs secretary edward j derwinski wrote whitten on 
tuesday that without the money workforce reductions and delayed 
purchases of medical equipment would occur the veterans medical 
program he said is in a state of emergency 
the measure was bogged down because of a dispute over 822 
million for antidrug efforts that it also contains the 
administration says the spending can wait until next year and 
threatened to veto the bill unless it was removed 
meanwhile congressional leaders and president bush met at the 
white house tuesday to discuss the fiscal 1991 budget the 
grammrudman deficitreduction law sets a deficit target of 64 
billion for that year and participants agree that meeting the goal 
will be difficult 
rep leon panetta dcalif chairman of the house budget 
committee said the meeting produced some good progress toward 
discussions on sticky subjects such as taxes and spending cuts 
the only specifics that we all discussed there was the fact 
that everything is going to have to be on the table defense 
entitlements taxes all three are going to have to be part of that 
kind of package he said 
there werent any violent reactions said house speaker jim 
wright of texas when reporters asked him how bush had reacted to 
suggestions of new taxes 
