<TEXT>
all people should be free to leave their homeland 
speakers said wednesday at an officially recognized conference on 
emigration rights held in the country most often publicly accused 
of violating them 
the right to leave is at the core of international 
humanitarian law said law professor irwin cotler of canadas 
mcgill university it is tantamount to the right to liberty and 
even i would say to the right to life 
speakers said the soviet record on emigration has improved under 
president mikhail s gorbachev but the improvements have not been 
guaranteed by law a new more liberal law on emigration is 
expected to emerge in the coming weeks 
foreign ministry official vladimir morozov said 108000 citizens 
emigrated from the soviet union in 1988 20 times as many as in 
1986 he admitted that emigration officials had often abused their 
positions but said the forthcoming law would make them more 
accountable 
the conference titled freedom of movement for all was 
sponsored by the international foundation for the survival and 
development of humanity soviet human rights activist andrei 
sakharov presides over the foundations human rights committee but 
could not attend 
the foundation was formed in moscow in january 1988 to direct 
studies on such threats to mankind as the arms race pollution and 
hunger it has offices in moscow stockholm and washington its 
soviet members include officials and unofficial figures 
in the first quarter of 1989 the soviet union granted 57000 
exit permits mainly to ethnic germans armenians pentecostalists 
and jews last month 4557 jews left the highest figure for any 
single month since jewish emigration peaked in october 1979 
president bush said last week he would ask congress to ease the 
jacksonvanik amendment which links trade concessions for 
communist countries to emigration performance provided moscow 
fulfills its promises on new laws and their enforcement 
among soviets attending the conference however many said they 
were still denied exit from the country largely because of their 
purported knowledge of state secrets elya varshavskaya 75 said 
she was not allowed to join her only son in denmark because she 
worked for the secret police more than 40 years ago 
soviet officials have said the new law on emigration will ease 
secrecy restrictions and probably repeal the requirement that a 
prospective emigrant have an invitation from a close relative 
in a summary of one report to be presented at the conference 
professor vladimir kartashkin recommends that passports for foreign 
travel be made available to any citizen who wants one and that a 
maximum of five years be set for the validity of state secrets 
kartashkin of the national academy of sciences institute of 
state and law also said soviets should not be deprived of 
citizenship if they leave to live abroad 
among soviet emigres stripped of their citizenship were ballet 
dancers mikhail baryshnikov and rudolf nureyev and cellist mstislav 
rostropovich they were denied entry to the soviet union until it 
recently began to welcome them back for visits ordinary emigrants 
also routinely lose their citizenship 
conference organizers distributed an appeal asking all 
governments that limit freedom of movement to bring their laws into 
line with international human rights agreements and encourage 
travel and emigration 
