<TEXT>
a house subcommittee moved wednesday to make 
banks disclose annual percentage yields and fees on savings and 
other deposit accounts but only after weakening the ability of 
consumers to sue if they dont 
the truth in savings legislation was approved unanimously by 
the house banking committees subcommittee on consumer affairs 
after it was amended to allow only actual account holders to sue 
over false advertising or other violations 
the bill is intended to outlaw what rep richard lehman 
dcalif the panels chairman called teaser rates and other 
misleading advertising by banks and other financial institutions in 
trying to attract deposits 
peggy miller of the consumer federation of america said banks 
now use snake oil practices to lure deposits and then play 
deceitful games through service fees undisclosed withdrawal 
penalties and inconsistent disclosures to cheat consumers out of 
earning the advertised yield on their accounts 
as an example she cited one days issue of the washington post 
in which advertisements for various financial institutions used 11 
different yield terms to describe the interest rates they were 
offering to depositors 
consumers confronted with this broad array of terminology can 
only throw up their hands in hopeless confusion and hope that they 
get the best deal possible she said 
the bill requires that banks savings and loans and credit 
unions clearly and conspicuously give the annual percentage yield 
most prominence in their advertising and also disclose any minimum 
balances necessary and the annual rate of simple interest 
the financial institutions also have to maintain and disclose 
fee schedules and terms and conditions applicable to each class of 
accounts they offer in order to provide consumers a meaningful 
way to compare deposit instruments 
account holders who believe those conditions were violated could 
sue for damages and attorneys fees plus penalities of 100 to 
1000 as an indiviudal or up to 500000 or 1 percent of an 
institutions net worth in classaction suits 
lehmans original version allowed anyone to file such a suit 
but it was amended on a 96 vote to cover only current account 
holders or those who had closed an account with the past year 
the amendment was approved after federal reserve board member 
martha seeger complained the sweeping civil liability 
provisions subject institutions to costly litigation by the 
public at large 
ms miller however said the amendment opens a loophole in 
which consumers who paid upfront application fees to open accounts 
but never actually did could never recover what they lost 
the bill was generally supported by banking groups after they 
succeeded in thwarting earlier attempts by lawmakers to make them 
adopt uniform methods for compounding interest accruals daily 
similar legislation was approved last year by both the house and 
senate but died in the waning days of the 100th congress a 
virtually identical bill except that it also applies to mutual 
funds has been introduced in the senate this year by sen 
christopher dodd dconn 
