<TEXT>
a senate panel wednesday approved legislation 
to lift remaining price controls on natural gas by 1993 nudging 
the energy industry one step closer to a longsought prize it says 
will benefit consumers as well as commerce 
experts generally agree that natural gas prices would be 
unlikely to rise immediately in reaction to ending price controls 
since the market price currently is well below the controlled 
price many industry officials predict however that growing 
demand for gas in the 1990s would likely push prices substantially 
higher 
with only sen howard metzenbaum dohio voicing strenuous 
objections the senate energy and natural resources committee 
approved the bill 172 the full senate may consider the bill as 
early next week although the timing was uncertain 
the house passed a nearly identical bill last month with 
virtually no dissent 
the legislation is strongly supported by the bush 
administration which has made gas decontrol a key feature of its 
evolving energy policy president bush echoing industry arguments 
in favor of decontrol has said the move would restore freemarket 
forces in an industry that has been under federal price controls 
since 1954 
industry groups have said price decontrol would stimulate more 
production of natural gas which currently accounts for about 
onequarter of the nations energy supply 
the legislation would complete a price decontrol process that 
began in 1978 with the natural gas policy act which removed price 
limits on certain kinds of gas while also establishing two dozen 
categories of gas each with a ceiling price 
some consumer groups have opposed the gas decontrol bill saying 
that while it might not trigger an immediate price rise it does 
nothing to correct other regulatory problems that mean higher costs 
to the 48 million households that use natural gas 
industrial users of natural gas generally favor the legislation 
it will stimulate new production and make more natural gas 
available at cheaper prices said jerry jasinowski chief 
economist of the national assocation of manufacturers 
metzenbaum a longstanding opponent of gas decontrol said he 
suspected the major oil companies that own about 45 percent of the 
nations gas reserves are holding a lot of gas off the market until 
the federal price controls are removed 
you may bet all the tea in china that natural gas prices will 
go up and go up substantially within a few years if price 
controls are ended he said calling the bill the most 
anticonsumer piece of legislation we have ever enacted 
sen bill bradley dnj also voted against the bill he said 
however that his position was based mainly on concern about how 
the legislation might affect federal regulatory authority over 
natural gas transportation he said he might reconsider his vote 
depending on how the transport issue was resolved on the senate 
floor 
the only major difference between the house and senate bills is 
that the house version would lift price controls on newly drilled 
wells immediately instead of in 1993 the senate bill has no such 
provision 
about onethird of us natural gas currently is subject to 
federal price controls 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

