<TEXT>
finally theres a little car with an automatic transmission 
thats peppy yet doesnt struggle even on tough inclines 
this gutsy competitor the 1989 subaru justy gl ecvt is the 
only car in the country with a newfangled continuously variable 
transmission that doesnt shift 
instead the transmissions powerflow is smooth and continuous 
and is designed to offer the fuel economy of a manual transmission 
and the ease of operation of an automatic 
the pricetag is under 8000 thats noteworthy when you 
consider that many major innovations usually show up first on 
upscale luxury cars that most buyers cant afford 
subaru decided last year not to follow the pack and introduced 
the justy gl ecvt for the 1989 model year after years of research 
and nearly two years of ecvt sales in japan 
the continuously variable transmission concept actually is about 
100 years old but subaru combined the idea with computer controls 
in its lightweight runabout the justy and was the first to bring 
such a transmission to america ford and fiat have cvts in europe 
basically the justys transmission operates through a pair of 
pulleys and a metal belt that smoothly transfers power from one 
pulley to another the transmission automatically and constantly 
adjusts its ratios to match engine revolutions and load to how fast 
the car is going 
theres no hunting for the appropriate gear in this car even in 
steep climbs 
the transmission workings are in an oil bath for cooler 
operation and longer life subaru says adding that the ecvt has 
fewer moving parts than conventional transmissions so theyre 
easier to make and repair the driver will notice none of these 
things all he or she has to do is put the gear lever in drive and 
press on the accelerator 
the justy test car with its little threecylinder engine ran 
smoothly as promised save for one cold 32degree morning when i 
felt one jerk as i tried to drive away from a cold start 
the fuel economy was decent too about 34 miles per gallon in 
rugged pedaltothemetal cityhighway driving thats the same 
as the 34 mpg rating for city driving in a fivespeed manual 
transmission justy where you have to shift 
as expected in a subcompact the justy test car offered easy 
maneuverability in and out of parking spaces but theres no power 
steering so it can take some effort to turn the wheels while at a 
standstill 
i also noticed a bit of torque steer when i pushed the 
accelerator all the way down during a right turn seating is for 
four and the nicely upholstered front seats felt fine the rear 
seat was stiff and benchlike though and there wasnt a lot of 
headroom for tall folks 
as expected in a subcompact legroom could be tight if the front 
seats were pushed all the way back the interior was plain with 
screws showing where the speakers were placed at the end of each 
side of the dashboard still fit and finish was admirable and 
there were no squeaks or creaks 
the justy had been a novel car from its start in 1987 its the 
only subcompact that has a fourwheeldrive version for 1989 
subaru added the twowheeldrive gl ecvt version and put in more 
passenger and luggage room to all justy models by lengthening them 
6 inches and adding another inch to the height larger tires and 
front brakes on the gl and rs models were other changes for 1989 
americans seem to have taken to both the two and 
fourwheeldrive justy models with combined sales rising from 
13240 in calendar 1987 to 29865 last year for the first four 
months of 1989 another 9342 including 3213 ecvt models were 
sold so the pace is about even with last year 
steve davis national manager of product relations at subaru 
said the companys goal is for 3000 ecvt sales per month in 
april 1044 were sold he said adding that good quantities of the 
ecvt were not available at dealerships until after january 
davis said the justy is especially popular with women they are 
59 percent of the buyers of the twowheeldrive justy and 51 
percent of the buyers of the fourwheeldrive justy buyers median 
age is between 31 and 34 and more than 72 percent have college 
education davis said 
median household income ranges from 25400 for buyers of the 
twowheeldrive justy to 32000 for buyers of the fourwheeldrive 
version 
a major competitor is the ford festiva which looks similar to 
the justy on the outside and starts at about 7000 for a twodoor 
hatchback with automatic transmission because the ecvt model is 
new for this model year consumer reports magazine does not have an 
owners trouble report 
</TEXT>
