african corporations anglo american corp of south africa and de 
beers consolidated mines ltd launched a hostile takeover bid for 
gold fields minorco already held almost 30 percent of gold fields 
shares 
gold fields and its us subsidiary newmont mining corp the 
largest gold producer in the united states sued in new york to 
block the takeover 
mukasey halted the takeover bid saying the combined entities 
would control 323 percent of the noncommunist worlds gold market 
on tuesday the judge said minorco had ample time to appeal his 
earlier rulings but for its own reasons and aware of the 
onrushing dealine minorco chose not to do so 
it should not now complain of unfair prejudice because it 
chose voluntarily a strategy which now leaves little time to 
appeal he wrote 
minorco owns or has tenders for about 55 percent of gold fields 
shares but mukaseys injunction bars minorco from buying shares it 
doesnt own the company said it would keep its position under 
close review 
britains panel on takeovers and mergers ordered gold fields to 
drop out of the us lawsuit unless it obtained shareholder 
approval gold fields voluntarily dropped out a week ago leaving 
newmont as the only obstacle to the takeover gold fields owns 49 
percent of newmont 
unless minorco could get newmont to withdraw its lawsuit the 
bid was to expire wednesday under british regulations 
in its last attempt to have the injunction lifted minorco 
claimed newmont lacked standing to continue the suit because it 
told the british takeovers panel it was a us concern not 
controlled by gold fields 
minorco lawyers claimed that if newmont was not controlled by 
gold fields it could not allege antitrust injury 
newmont originally claimed that because its us operations were 
more efficient than minorcos south african mines minorco 
eventually would shut down us operations if the takeover were 
accomplished 
in upholding mukaseys earlier rulings a federal appeals court 
said last month that newmonts threatened injury is precisely the 
type that the antitrust laws were designed to protect against 
mukasey wrote that the premise of minorcos argument was 
incorrect 
newmont could suffer antitrust injury in the form of 
reduced control over pricing and output as an independent 
competitor if the takeover succeeded and minorco controlled a 
greater share of the world noncommunist gold market he wrote 
he added that newmont has standing as an independent 
competitor to allege that the resulting combination of gold fields 
and minorco would substantially lessen competition and injure it 
</TEXT>
