karen oconnor vice president of aemmp record 
co hypes the companys latest release in the best tradition of 
music promoters 
i really havent heard anything in a long time that was 
powerful as this music she says its a lot better than what 
ive been hearing on the radio lately 
oconnor is pushing a record but if she pushes a bit too hard 
perhaps shes entitled the record by the bad examples will be 
aemmps sole release this year and the executive is only 20 years 
old 
aemmp pronounced amp is a real record company owned by 
columbia college a private liberalarts school in downtown chicago 
with an enrollment of about 6500 
aemmp also is a class company executives and workers are 
students learning to operate what singersongwriter joni mitchell 
once called the starmaker machinery behind the popular songs 
for oconnor who quit two parttime jobs and spent her spring 
break in chicago to devote more time to this years project the 
class could become a springboard to a job with a major record 
company and advance her toward the goal of managing a bigname 
rocker 
this class is going to give us great resumes she said 
the objective of the class called decisionmaking music 
business is to find a musical act sign it to a contract 
manufacture and market its record and get the band signed to a 
major record company 
so success for oconnor and her approximately 20 classmates also 
would give a boost to the bad examples a poprock quartet selected 
by the class from among about 200 acts as the brightest star on 
chicagos club scene 
the more different people that are excited about the music and 
working for it the better it helps us said ralph covert the 
groups songwriter and lead singer 
aemmp released the threesong set by the bad examples on april 
26 in two formats 800 12inch vinyl records and 200 cassette 
tapes the recordrelease party at a chicagoarea nightspot marked 
the completion of the production phase of the project and the 
beginning of the marketing push which includes pestering radio 
stations into playing the music 
if youre going pop you cant exist without airplay said 
chuck suber a cocreator of the class you cant even get into a 
record store without something thats been presold on the air 
oconnor said aemmp would pitch the bad examples release to all 
national record companies but she said it was at least as 
important to promote the band via airplay club appearances 
perhaps even a concert tour of college towns 
if we start a buzz in chicago theyre going to be that much 
more interested in the product she said 
the aemmp records class was founded in 1982 by suber who had 
just stepped down after 24 years as publisher of down beat 
magazine a jazz monthly and irwin steinberg who had just retired 
as chairman of new yorkbased polygram records inc 
suber also had taught parttime for many years in columbias 
arts entertainment and media management program for which the 
inhouse record company is named although the department is now 
