cocoa prices hit a 14year low wednesday before 
recovering to finish the day higher on the london market 
the selling wave reflected the prospect of a glutted market for 
the fifth consecutive season in 198889 traders said 
cocoa for july delivery closed at 1158 a metric ton up 164 
from tuesdays close earlier in the day the contract traded at 
the 14year low of 1140 
traders said most experts are predicting record world production 
this season of about 23 million metric tons that would be about 
200000 metric tons more than expected consumption the biggest 
surplus ever 
in addition signs that the ivory coast which has 
international debts of more than 14 billion could be close to 
abandoning its costly pricesupport policy also have encouraged 
selling traders said 
the present price the government pays its cocoa farmers is equal 
to about 1312 a ton traders said 
ivory coasts international creditors have been pressing 
strongly for a cut for some time according to banking sources 
ivory coast which is africas biggest producer and relies on 
cocoa for about a third of its export revenues has for the past 
year been refusing to sell at a price below its breakeven level 
as a result the nation has accumulated stocks of about 400000 
tons of which half already have been put into storage in europe 
for at least two years 
