<TEXT>
a federal judge has signed a consent decree 
formally ending a nearly 4year printers strike against the chicago 
tribune 
both sides had previously accepted and signed the basic accord 
which includes an 856 million settlement fund a new threeyear 
contract and withdrawal of a federal lawsuit filed by the chicago 
typographical union no 16 
us district judge marvin aspen signed the consent decree 
monday 
fiftyone printers who accepted a 1986 unconditional offer to 
return to work can remain under terms of the new contract which 
took effect jan 3 or take a 30000 buyout 
of the 240 original strikers 119 remain out of work they will 
receive lumpsum payments based on age and tenure ranging from 
about 30000 to 90000 and will receive companypaid medical 
insurance after age 65 
the strike resulted from the tribunes desire to gain greater 
control in hiring and assigning printers in the composing room 
the printers lawsuit alleged the company had violated a 1975 
agreement in which they were guaranteed lifetime employment in 
exchange for the introduction of laborsaving technology 
</TEXT>
