<TEXT>
steel imports in march fell to their lowest 
level in six years and their share of the domestic market shrank to 
172 percent well within the goal of the us import quotas a 
domestic industry group said wednesday 
the months 122 million tons of imports represented just 129 
percent of the market when excluding 129000 tons of semifinished 
steel us companies imported to supply their own mills according 
to an importers group 
semifinished imports have been in critical demand by us 
rolling mills since early 1988 said john griffin president of 
the american institute for imported steel of new york which 
represents importers 
exports meanwhile rose in march to 606000 tons the largest 
monthly total since july 1974 
first quarter exports totaled 11 million tons compared with 
303000 tons in the 1988 first quarter the american iron and steel 
institute in washington which represents domestic producers said 
the rival groups interpret commerce department information to 
serve their competing interests 
the domestic group said steel prices in foreign markets are 
higher than in the united states making this country less 
attractive to foreign producers 
the leading steelproducing nations appear to be shipping less 
metal in than authorized under the individual quotas they 
negotiated with the united states the aisi said foreign producers 
undershipped their quotas by 25 percent last year 
imports were 134 million tons in february and 184 million tons 
in march 1988 
the 122 million tons shipped this march was the lowest since 
april 1983 the import tonnage represented even less of the 
domestic supply because shipments by us producers were higher 
that month the aisi said 
the fiveyear quotas instituted by former president reagan in 
late 1984 were intended to limit foreign steel to around 20 percent 
of the us market domestic steelmakers are campaigning to have 
them renewed beyond their sept 31 expiration 
</TEXT>
