<TEXT>
a united auto workers local election 
completed wednesday shows division in the union over the 
japanesestyle team concept management adopted a year ago at 
general motors corps local camaro factory 
candidates unhappy with the system at gms van nuys plant won 
five of seven positions as local 645s delegates to the uaws 
annual national convention which runs june 1822 in anaheim 
opponents believe the company takes advantage of cooperative 
management to erase work rules it couldnt negotiate away at the 
bargaining table union leaders want to give the concept a chance 
the van nuys plant has about 4000 workers voting began 
tuesday with night shift workers casting their ballots early 
wednesday morning 
the five successful candidates who ran as opponents of the team 
concept were cal gutierrez 876 votes pete lopez 846 votes jake 
flukers 760 votes leroy padilla 709 votes and mark masaoka 699 
votes 
the two other winners who favor the team concept were 
bargaining committee chairman richard ruppert 828 votes and 
financial secretarytreasurer joe garcia 758 votes 
results were released by the unions assistant regional 
director henry gonzalez who said the local president and vice 
president did not run 
opponents of team management are part of a nationwide movement 
within the uaw that calls itself new directions and favors a more 
confrontational approach to gm management led by union locals at 
gm plants around st louis and detroit the movement is expected to 
challenge the unions leadership at the convention 
gonzalez argued in an interview tuesday that the team system is 
slowly improving the lot of workers in van nuys he suggested the 
issue was created to use against union leaders 
anybody thats on the outside looking in has to create an 
issue to run against and i guess their issue is the team 
concept gonzalez said 
the team management system was instituted last year at plant 
which produces chevrolet camaros and pontiac firebirds 
the change came after current union leaders won a close election 
in june 1988 ousting officers opposed to cooperation 
under the new system workers are divided into teams of six and 
those teams take part in decisions on how their jobs will be done 
backers note the systems give a worker the power to stop the 
assembly line to make sure his or her task is done right that 
power is said to be a key ingredient in worker satisfaction 
dissidents point to temporary layoffs imposed at the plant since 
then to buttress their argument that the new system didnt really 
save jobs as it was supposed to 
management says the socalled rolling layoffs were needed 
because of lack of demand for the cars the other camaro and 
firebird plant in norwood ohio was shut down and some in the 
union believe that was because the company saw the van nuys 
workforce as more accommodating 
</TEXT>
