american telephone amp telegraph co said 
wednesday it would cut certain longdistance prices by about 140 
million to comply with a new federal regulatory plan 
the price cuts will take effect on july 1 the same time the 
federal communications commissions new pricecap plan begins 
under the pricecap plan adopted march 16 the fcc limits the 
prices atampt charges rather than the profits it makes 
the new cuts will bring rates for consumers and small businesses 
down to the maximum permitted by the new regulation atampt spokesman 
bryant steele said 
atampts prices for large businesses had already been brought 
below the price cap 
the latest decrease will bring atampts total interstate 
longdistance price reductions to almost 40 percent in the five 
years since the bell system breakup the company said 
mci communications corp spokeswoman pam small said the mandated 
cut was not a surprise its a small number probably smaller 
than we would have expected she said 
us sprint communications co spokesman syd courson said the 
company would have no comment until its analysts had scanned the 
price filing 
under the filing 
prices on general longdistance service will drop about 60 
million a year 
the reach out america discount calling plan for consumers will 
be expanded at no extra charge prices of the basic and evening 
bonus versions of reach out america will be cut 
the international reach out calling plan will be expanded from 
four to 25 countries 
atampt will cut prices on calls its customers make between mexico 
and the united states and on calls from the united states to the 
philippines denmark the faeroe islands in the north atlantic 
finland norway and sweden atampt also will cut prices on 
international calls from puerto rico and the us virgin islands 
when holidays occur during the weekend but are legally observed 
on a weekday atampt will apply its holiday prices on the weekday the 
holiday is observed 
