the air force is reviewing a recommendation 
that it cancel a 204 million contract for radar warning receivers 
for f16 aircraft because the company obtained confidential 
information about its competitors product a spokesman said 
wednesday 
the general accounting office a congressional watchdog agency 
recommended this week that the air force terminate its dec 20 
contract with loral systems manufacturing co for 19 advanced 
radar warning receivers the agency cited information from 
documents released in the investigation of alleged pentagon fraud 
and corruption in its procurement of weapons 
litton systems inc a competitor with loral for the contract 
had filed a protest after documents from operation ill wind 
alleged that william galvin a defense consultant obtained 
information on littons proposal from victor cohen the deputy for 
tactical systems in the office of the assistant secretary of the 
air force for acquisition 
the contract awarded 204 million to loral for the 19 
receivers but had options that could lead to the production of 673 
additional receivers for a total of 188 million 
major donna pastor an air force spokeswoman said the service 
is reviewing the gao decision in the interim the air force has 
taken steps to preclude the obligation of any additional funds on 
the contract beyond the 204 million pastor said 
we wont exercise any production options until the service 
completes its review she said 
the air force has until january 1990 to decide on whether to go 
ahead on one of the production options with loral but pastor said 
the service would decide on the gao recommendation well before that 
the air force can accept the agencys recommendation ask it to 
reconsider the decision or reject it outright if it rejects the 
decision the service must inform the gao within 60 days 
the documents unsealed dec 27 alleged that galvin who served 
as a consultant for loral and litton obtained information from 
cohen about littons proposal and passed it on to loral 
whether or not the air force official was involved in the 
actual release the record establishes that procurement sensitive 
documents in the air forces possession concerning littons product 
were obtained by loral the gao said 
the air force argued that even if the allegations are true it 
would be difficult to conclude that loral took advantage of the 
improperly acquired information according to the gao 
no charges have been filed against galvin or cohen galvin has 
been suspended from dealings with the pentagon while cohen remains 
in his post at the air force however he is no longer involved in 
the awarding of contracts pastor said 
 
