<TEXT>
us automakers will have to improve fuel economy 
to 275 miles per gallon on 1990 passenger models transportation 
secretary samuel skinner said wednesday 
im hopeful this will be an incentive to auto makers to 
explore better ways to develop better engines and get better 
mileage skinner said at a news conference after a speech to the 
chicago association of commerce and industry 
weve got to get beyond where we are today in miles per 
gallon if were going to deal with this energy crisis he said 
the united states is importing more than 8 million barrels of oil a 
day for the first time since the 1970s 
the new standard will be 1 mile per gallon more efficient than 
the current 265 milepergallon level for 1989 models set by the 
department of transportation and 15 miles per gallon higher than 
the standard in the three previous model years the department said 
in a news release 
it was 1975 when congress passed the energy policy and 
conservation act giving the transportation department authority to 
set the corporate average fuel economy standard for passenger 
cars sold in the united states 
the standard known as the cafe is the average fuel economy 
measured over the automakers entire fleets 
although the standard is tough ford will comply said 
donald r buist a spokesman for ford motor co in dearborn mich 
for the longer term alternative ways of measuring fueleconomy 
progress should be considered 
william noack a spokesman for general motors corp in 
washington dc said cafe is a misguided regulatory program that 
doesnt save energy but does endanger us jobs by restricting 
the number of familysize americanmade cars manufacturers can 
produce 
we will of course do all we can do to meet the requirements 
even though it is hard to understand why there is such a law 
that is harmful to us fullline manufacturers and therefore to 
us jobs 
noack said cafe makes larger cars less available giving 
consumers one of three options keep their less fuelefficient 
cars buy trucks or vans also less fuel efficient but not covered 
by cafe or buy larger cars made by foreign manufacturers 
though foreignmade cars sold in the united states are governed 
by the cafe standard most foreign manufacturers have accrued 
credits under the program by marketing highly fuelefficient cars 
in past years and can now sell bigger cars without penalty he said 
ben dunn a spokesman with chrysler motors in highland park 
mich said chrysler did not take a position on the petition to 
roll back the 1990 cafe standards because the company has always 
met the standard chrysler sells a larger proportion of small cars 
and has higher fuel economy when averaged over its fleet 
if automakers fail to comply with the cafe standard they would 
incur hundreds and hundreds of millions of dollars in fines so 
the statute enforces itself skinner said 
the secretary who was in chicago as part of national 
transportation week observances said he could not estimate how 
much of a saving in fuel the new standard would produce nationally 
bob marx a spokesman at skinners office in washington said 
the figures were not immediately available 
</TEXT>
