<TEXT>
a former us food and drug administration 
chemist snared in the governments investigation of fda corruption 
pleaded guilty wednesday to federal charges he accepted 9600 in 
bribes from drug companies 
david j brancato 38 pleaded guilty in us district court to 
three counts of accepting bribes between 1986 and 1988 from 
officials with two drug companies that had products up for review 
by the fda 
the 38yearold rockville man faces up to six years in prison 
and 750000 in fines 
gary p jordan first assistant us attorney for maryland told 
judge john r hargrove that brancato had a reputation in the 
generic drug industry for being a fast and efficient reviewer of 
applications 
several drug manufacturers had expressed an interest in having 
him review their applications jordan said 
the investigation which is continuing has not turned up any 
evidence that bad drugs reached the public jordan said 
the first guilty plea in the probe of the fdas divison of 
generic drugs in rockville came monday when denver drug company 
execuitve raj maktari 48 admitted paying a 2000 bribe to former 
fda supervisor charles y chang 
maktari vice president for regulatory affairs and product 
development for pharmaceutical basics inc faces up to two years 
in prison and a 250000 fine on the charge 
chang who supervised chemists reviews of generic drug 
applications has been charged with receiving gratuities from drug 
companies 
according to evidence presented to hargrove maktari gave chang 
2000 in cash in august 1987 after chang said he was having 
financial difficulties 
at the time chang and his chemists were reviewing several 
applications for new drugs from maktaris company 
chang has also been accused of receiving a free trip to hong 
kong and thousands of dollars in furniture from a drug company in 
new york 
the investigation began last summer after a us house 
subcommittee turned up allegations of corruption involving 
government employees consultants and drug company executives 
brancato chang and maktari are cooperating with investigators 
prosecutors said 
sentencing dates were not announced 
</TEXT>
